	<h3>‘Bubble Harp’, ‘Gravilux’. ‘Antograph’, and ‘Tripolar’ iPad Installations</h3>
	<img src="/images/ipad_installations.jpg" alt="ipad_installations" title="ipad_installations" width="300px" />
	<p>Scott Snibbe's apps for the iPad were surprise bestsellers in Apple's app store last year, with over 400,000 downloads. These four works: Gravilux, Bubble Harp, Antograph, and Tripolar were created as screen- and web-based works of interactive art between 1997 and 2002, later adapted to the iPad and iPhone, and recently the Mac app store. All four works are what scientists call a dynamic system: a model of natural, mathematical or algorithmic reality. These systems let you touch an immaterial world that has consistent and predictable reactions, and the infinite variety of nature. Although there are few surprises when you visit a beach or pond, the experience is subtly different each time. Similarly, with these artworks the intention is for a person to feel an instant and intuitive sense of presence and control, while spending more time with a system provides greater reward. Like a musical instrument, the effect of the program on the mind is equal to the effect of the mind on the program. <br/>
		<ul>
		<li style="margin: 0px 0px 4px 0px;"><a href="http://www.snibbe.com/store/bubbleharp/" target="blank">Bubble Harp</a> draws bubble-like geometric diagrams around your fingertips, creating an ever-changing musical composition based on its structure.</li>
		<li style="margin: 0px 0px 4px 0px;"><a href="http://www.snibbe.com/store/gravilux/" target="blank">Gravilux</a> lets you draw with stars.</li>
		<li style="margin: 0px 0px 4px 0px;"><a href="http://www.snibbe.com/store/antograph/" target="blank">Antograph</a> streams ants from your fingertips.</li>
		<li style="margin: 0px 0px 4px 0px;"><a href="http://www.snibbe.com/store/tripolar/" target="blank">Tripolar</a> simulates a chaotic pendulum as a metaphor for our minds.</li>
		</ul>
	</p>
	
